Walkshed analysis - Los Angeles Example

Carole Voulgaris

9/17/2021

Setup

Youll need to increase the memory for R5R and load the required libraries.

# increase memory for r5r
options(java.parameters = "-Xmx2G")

library(sf) # spatial data package
library(tidycensus) # for retrieving census data
library(tidyverse) # for everything
library(r5r) # for getting transit sf features and calculating walk times

Get census data (with geometry)

In this example, Im just getting a set of race/ethnicity variables for each census block.

Im also generating a set of points for the centroid of each census block. Since Ill be using those centroid points to build a travel time matrix, Ill need to rename the GEOID column to be called id and tranform the data to WGS 84 (both requirements of the travel_time_matrix() function in R5R).

pop_by_race = c(total = "P005001",
                nh_white = "P005003",
                nh_black = "P005004",
                nh_asian = "P005006",
                hispanic = "P005010")

la_blocks <- get_decennial(geography = "block",
                           state = "CA",
                           county = "Los Angeles",
                           variables = pop_by_race,
                           geometry = TRUE,
                           output = "wide") %>%
  st_transform(crs = "WGS84")

la_centroids <- st_centroid(la_blocks) %>%
  rename(id = "GEOID")

Get transit route and stop locations

Before running any of the following, youll need to make sure you have the GTFS network that was in place on Feb 1, 2020 in the Networks/LA/1Feb folder. That folder also needs to contain PBF file with the OpenStreetMap network for the area covered by the transit network.

First, set up the R5R core.

r5r_core <- setup_r5("Networks/LA/1Feb", verbose = FALSE)

Now, use R5R to extract the transit routes and stop locations. Since well be using the stop locations to build a travel time matrix, well need to change the name of the stop_index column to id.

transit <- transit_network_to_sf(r5r_core)

transit_routes <- transit$routes 

transit_stops <- transit$stops %>%
  rename(id = stop_index)

Generate travel time matrix

Well build a travel time matrix to calculate the travel time from each transit stop to each census block centroid. Were setting a maximum trip duration of ten minutes, so our matrix will only include census blocks within a ten-minute walk of a transit stop.

Were done with R5R now, so we can free up some memory by stopping the R5R core.

ttm <- travel_time_matrix(r5r_core = r5r_core,
                          origins = transit_stops,
                          destinations =la_centroids,
                          mode = "WALK",
                          max_trip_duration = 10,
                          verbose = FALSE)
stop_r5(r5r_core)

Generate walksheds with route-level data

Now well get all the unique GEOIDs from the toId column of the travel time matrix. This is a list of census blocks with a centroid within a 10-minute walk of a transit stop.

Then Ill use that list to filter the LA County census blocks to only include those within walking distance of transit and do a spatial join to identify which transit route serves each of those blocks.

transit_block_list <- unique(ttm$toId)

transit_blocks <- la_blocks %>%
  filter(GEOID %in% transit_block_list) %>%
  st_join(transit_routes, st_nearest_feature)

Now, I can combine all the blocks that serve the same route and calculate population totals and percentages within each routes walkshed.

transit_walksheds <- transit_blocks %>%
  group_by(route_id) %>%
  summarize(total = sum(total),
            nh_white = sum(nh_white),
            nh_black = sum(nh_black),
            nh_asian = sum(nh_asian),
            hispanic = sum(hispanic),
            geometry = st_union(geometry),
            route_id = first(route_id),
            short_name = first(short_name),
            mode = first(mode)) %>%
  mutate(pct_nh_white = 100 * nh_white / total,
         pct_nh_black = 100 * nh_black / total,
         pct_nh_asian = 100 * nh_asian / total,
         pct_hispanic = 100 * hispanic / total)

Now I can plot the results on a map.

ggplot(transit_walksheds) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = pct_nh_white), color = NA, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_sf(data = transit_routes, color = "black", alpha = 0.2) +
 # geom_sf(data = transit_stops, color = "black", size = 0.05, alpha = 0.1) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(name = "Non-Hispanic\nwhite share of\npopulation served\nby route",
                       breaks = breaks <- seq(0,80, by = 20),
                       labels = paste(breaks, "%", sep = "")) +
  theme_void()

Im also interested in seeing how a histogram of this distribution

ggplot(transit_walksheds) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = pct_nh_white), 
                 bins = 40,
                 color = "black",
                 fill = "gray") +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Non-Hispanic white share of population served by route",
                     breaks = breaks <- seq(0,100, by = 20),
                     labels = paste(breaks, "%", sep = "")) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Number of routes") +
  theme_bw()
